(144, 'jcdvuYlkFKA', 'paper_reference', 'creative', 'none', 'narrative', '10.1111/brv.12055', '10.1111/brv.12055', 'Coastal Carbon', 'Find out more: http://www.rodconnolly.com/coastal-carbon\n\nVideography by Bodhi Connolly & Jean Davis.\n\nThe world runs on carbon. Whether it\'s fuelling the world\'s energy needs through hydrocarbons or driving critical food webs, everyone\'s interested in tracking carbon pathways through food webs. We are investigating two key aspects of carbon movement: carbon sequestration in the coastal strip and food webs.\n\nKey papers:\n\nHyndes G, Nagelkerken I, McLeod R, Connolly RM, Lavery P, Vanderklift M (2014) Mechanisms and ecological role of carbon transfer within coastal seascapes. Biological Reviews (doi: 10.1111/brv.12055)\n\nConnolly RM, Schlacher TA (2013) Sample acidification significantly alters stable isotope ratios of sulfur in aquatic plants and animals. Marine Ecology Progress Series 493:1-8\n\nHuijbers CM, Schlacher TA, Schoeman DS, Weston MA, Connolly RM (2013) Urbanisation alters processing of marine carrion on sandy beaches. Landscape and Urban Planning 119:1-8', '2014-04-25 01:43:46', 'Carbon, coast, coastal, chemicals, science, rod connolly, mangrove, mangroves, saltmarsh, marsh, seagrass, seaweed, algae, fish, mud, research, scientific, field work, griffith, gold coast, blue carbon, ecosystems, food webs, Griffith University (Organization), marine biology, estuarine, estuary, ecology, stable isotope, moreton bay, Commonwealth Scientific And Industrial Research Organisation (Government Agency), csiro, fisheries, sustainable, environment, wetland, queensland, Australia (Country)', NULL, NULL, 'Rod Connolly', 'UCY_sMZ6yqTP-L3fGT4DSbYQ', 129, 288, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, '2020-07-27 00:49:07'),
